Explain in detail how a transformer language model performs next token prediction, covering attention, MLPs, and the residual stream. Be specific about dimensions for a 14B parameter model with 5120 hidden size. Also, explain the difference between the transformer model and the GPT-3 architecture.
Okay, I need to explain how a transformer language model does next token prediction, focusing on attention, MLPs, and the residual stream. Plus, I need to cover specific dimensions for a 14B model with 5120 hidden size. Also, compare the transformer model to GPT-3. Let me break this down.

First, I remember that transformer models use self-attention mechanisms. So, during next token prediction, the model looks at the context (previous tokens) to determine the next token. The attention mechanism allows each position to attend to all other positions, capturing dependencies regardless of distance. But how does this work in detail?

The input is tokenized and converted to embeddings. Then, the model processes each token through multiple layers. Each layer has two main parts: the self-attention sublayer and the feed-forward (FFN) sublayer, both with residual connections. The residual stream is the flowing tensor that gets updated at each layer, allowing information to flow through the network.

